President Joseph R. Biden Jr. has proclaimed May 2022 as Jewish American Heritage Month. In his proclamation, he recognizes the contributions and resilience of Jewish Americans throughout history. He highlights the arrival of 23 Jewish refugees in 1654, who faced resistance but secured the right to settle in America, expanding the frontier of religious freedoms. President Biden acknowledges the role of Jewish Americans in shaping the nation through their commitment to democracy, fighting for justice, equality, and freedom. He emphasizes the importance of standing against bigotry and antisemitic violence, and his administration's efforts to combat hate crimes and protect religious organizations. The proclamation also recognizes the cultural, scientific, artistic, and intellectual contributions of Jewish Americans, as well as their advocacy for civil and political rights. President Biden calls upon all Americans to learn more about the heritage and contributions of Jewish Americans and observe the month with appropriate programs and activities.